My present object is to present the results of that work in a more systematic form, and, at the same time, to enter somewhat more fully into certain points, which in that work have been only incidentally touched upon.

Even when we leave out of· consideration the possibility of oceanic streams being produced by extratelluric attraction, there are, it is known, many causes, which give rise to motion in the ocean’s water: gain or loss of heat, rain, evaporation, freezing, variation of atmospheric pressure, winds etc., are causes of this kind, all arising directly or indirectly from unequal distribution of the solar heat. All the learned men, who have made the problem of the origin of the oceanic currente a subject of study, have paid more or less attention to all these causes, though often in a one-sided manner, so that an almost exclusive importance has been attributed sometimes to one and sometimes to another.
